10. PINHOLE CAMERA & PERSPECTIVE PROJECTION
------------------------------------------------------------

CONCEPT:
  - A 3D point (X, Y, Z) in the real world gets projected onto
    a 2D image plane using a pinhole camera model
  - The camera is at the origin (0, 0, 0)
  - The image plane sits at distance f (focal length) along Z axis

PROJECTION FORMULA:
  x_proj = f * X / Z
  y_proj = f * Y / Z
  - Divide by Z = objects farther away appear smaller (perspective!)
  - f = focal length (controls zoom/field of view)

CODE:
  f = 5   # focal length

  points_3D = np.array([
      [X1, Y1, Z1],
      [X2, Y2, Z2],
      ...
  ])

  X, Y, Z = points_3D[:,0], points_3D[:,1], points_3D[:,2]

  x_proj = f * X / Z     # projected x on image plane
  y_proj = f * Y / Z     # projected y on image plane
  z_proj = np.ones_like(x_proj) * f   # all projected points sit at z=f

  points_proj = np.column_stack((x_proj, y_proj, z_proj))

VISUALIZING IN 3D:
  fig = plt.figure()
  ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')   # 3D axes

  ax.scatter(x, y, z, s=80)    # plot points (s = dot size)
  ax.text(x, y, z, "label")    # add text label at a point

  # Draw image plane as a flat surface at z=f
  xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(-3,3,2), np.linspace(-3,3,2))
  zz = np.ones_like(xx) * f
  ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, zz, alpha=0.2)   # alpha = transparency

  # Draw rays from camera to 3D points
  ax.plot([x_start, x_end], [y_start, y_end], [z_start, z_end])

  ax.view_init(elev=20, azim=40)   # set camera viewing angle
  ax.set_xlabel("X")
  ax.set_ylabel("Y")
  ax.set_zlabel("Z")

KEY CONCEPTS TO REMEMBER:
  - Focal length f  -> larger f = more zoom, narrower view
  - Z in denominator -> larger Z (farther) = smaller projected point
  - Image plane is at Z = f
  - Camera sits at origin (0,0,0)
  - np.column_stack() joins arrays as columns into one matrix

